# Comparison of Common Sorting Algorithms in Big O Notation

Sorting algorithms are fundamental in computer science and understanding their complexities is valuable. Here's an analysis of common sorting algorithms using Big O notation:

- **Bubble Sort**: Best case is O(n) when the list is already sorted. Average and worst case are O(n^2).
- **Insertion Sort**: Best and average case is O(n^2). Worst case is O(n^2) as well.
- **Selection Sort**: Always O(n^2), no matter the initial arrangement of data.
- **Merge Sort**: Always O(n log n), as it splits the list in half and then combines them.
- **Quick Sort**: Best case is O(n log n), average case is O(n log n), and the worst case is O(n^2) when the pivot elements are the smallest or largest element in the sub-list.
- **Heap Sort**: Always O(n log n), as it constructs a heap from the input data and extracts elements from the heap one by one to produce a sorted list.

Here's C++ code example for each of these sorting algorithms:

### Bubble Sort

```cpp
#include <iostream>
#include <vector>

void bubbleSort(std::vector<int>& arr) {
    int n = arr.size();
    for(int i = 0; i < n-1; i++) {
        for(int j = 0; j < n-i-1; j++) {
            if(arr[j] > arr[j+1]) {
                std::swap(arr[j], arr[j+1]);
            }
        }
    }
}

void printArray(const std::vector<int>& arr) {
    for (int num : arr) {
        std::cout << num << ' ';
    }
    std::cout << '\n';
}

int main() {
    std::vector<int> arr = {64, 34, 25, 12, 22, 11, 90};
    bubbleSort(arr);
    printArray(arr);
    return 0;
}
